        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down.</hi> | Beckenham | <hi rend="print">Kent. S.E.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>April 27</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I write one line merely to thank you very much for your note &amp; to say that I hope you will accept from me a copy of my Journal of Travels, which as you are so good a scholar might possibly in parts interest you.— I have told my publisher to send you a copy by Post.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/> It does not seem possible that the spurs of the two species of Pavo will ever differ in rate of development.<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>With my best thanks | Pray believe me | Dear Sir | Yours truly obliged | Charles Darwin</p>
<p>P.S. | If hereafter you sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> perceive any difference in the development of the spurs, perhaps you will have the great kindness to inform me.—<ref target="#foot.f4"/></p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">0.1 Beckenham] <hi rend="italic">interl before del</hi> ‘<hi rend="italic">Bromley</hi>’ </note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n2">1.5 rate of] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi> </note>
            </div>

            
            
            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-6711.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from J. N. Hegt, [23 April 1869]</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD refers to his <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_4250.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Journal of researches</hi></ref>, and to his publisher, John Murray.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-6711.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from J. N. Hegt, [23 April 1869]</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">In <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1966.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi></ref> 1: 290 n. 28, where CD cited Hegt’s information on the peafowl, he added, ‘I presume that I should have been informed if any difference in the rate of development had subsequently been observed.’</note>
        </div>        
            
